:"about 1169","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Erskine, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Erskine, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Erskine","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the barony of Erskine in Renfrewshire, first recorded in 1226 in the form <i>Erskyn</i>.","History: A family of this name have held a number of Scottish titles, including the earldoms of Mar, Buchan, Kellie, and Rosslyn."],"variants":[{"name":"Erskin","meanings":["Scottish (central Scotland and Fife): variant of   Erskine  . This form of the surname is now more common in the US."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Henry David Erskine ,Earl of Buchan was born in 1147 as the son of Ninian De Erskine and Elizabeth Mitchell. He had at least 2 sons with Mary Stewart. He died in 1226, in Scotland, at the age of 79."},"et":{"1147–1226":"1147–1226","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","1169–Male":"1169–Surnud","1170–1190":"1170–1190","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1190":"1190","aft 1190":"pärast 1190","1226":"1226","1147":"1147","1169":"1169","about 1169":"umbes 1169","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Erskine, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Erskine, Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirling, Stirlingshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1147–1226":"1147–1226","1150–Female":"1150–Kuollut","1169–Male":"1169–Kuollut","1170–1190":"1170–1190","1120–Male":"1120–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1190":"1190","aft 1190":"1190 jälkeen","1226":"1226","1147":"1147","1169":"1169","about 1169":"noin 1169","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Erskine, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Erskine, Renfrewshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Scotland","Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirling, Stirlingshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1147–1226":"1147–1226","1150–Female":"1150–Décédée","1169–Male":"1169–Décédé","1170–1190":"1170–1190","1120–Male":"1120–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1190":"1190","aft 1190":"après 1190","1226":"1226","1147":"1147","1169":"1169","about 1169":"environ 1169","1120":"1120","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","Erskine, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Erskine, Renfrewshire, Écosse, Royaume-